Now run the cluster analysis by 1. Calculating distance 2. Using Wards distance to form clusters

d <- dist(putils)
summary(d)
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
  1.384   3.137   3.902   3.865   4.573   6.461 
fit.w <- hclust(d,method="ward.D")
plot(fit.w,hang=-1,cex=0.8,main="Ward linking clusters")

Now, let us examine the results for different cluster sizes When you save the notebook, an HTML file containing the code and output will be saved alongside it (click the Preview button or press Ctrl+Shift+K to preview the HTML file).

Let us now perform k-means clustering. Note that you have to specify the number of clusters

library(NbClust)
set.seed(1234)
devAskNewPage(ask=T)
nc <- NbClust(putils,min.nc=2,max.nc=5,method="kmeans")
*** : The Hubert index is a graphical method of determining the number of clusters.
                In the plot of Hubert index, we seek a significant knee that corresponds to a 
                significant increase of the value of the measure i.e the significant peak in Hubert
                index second differences plot. 
 

*** : The D index is a graphical method of determining the number of clusters. 
                In the plot of D index, we seek a significant knee (the significant peak in Dindex
                second differences plot) that corresponds to a significant increase of the value of
                the measure. 
 
******************************************************************* 
* Among all indices:                                                
* 3 proposed 2 as the best number of clusters 
* 6 proposed 3 as the best number of clusters 
* 7 proposed 4 as the best number of clusters 
* 7 proposed 5 as the best number of clusters 

                   ***** Conclusion *****                            
 
* According to the majority rule, the best number of clusters is  4 
 
 
******************************************************************* 

table(nc$Best.n[1,])

0 1 2 3 4 5 
2 1 3 6 7 7 
barplot(table(nc$Best.n[1,]),
        xlab="Number of Clusters", ylab="Number of criteria",

mh <- read.csv("Mass Housing.dat")
head(mh)

The objective is to predict the market value

set.seed(1234)
train <- sample(nrow(mh), 0.7*nrow(mh)) # create a training set

Now fit the tree

library(rpart)
set.seed(1234)
dtree <- rpart(mvalue~.,data=mh.train,method="anova",
  parms=list(split="information"))

We now do classification trees. Read the Freshmen1.dat file

fm <- read.csv("Freshmen1.dat")
fm$return <- factor(fm$return, levels=c(0,1),
                    labels=c("Does not return","Returns"))
head(fm)

Create a training and validation set

set.seed(1234)
train <- sample(nrow(fm), 0.7*nrow(fm)) # create a training set
fm.train <- fm[train,]
fm.validate <- fm[-train,]
table(fm.train$return)

Does not return         Returns 
             17              53 
table(fm.validate$return)

Does not return         Returns 
              6              24

Run the classification tree. Note the method is now “class”

library(rpart)
set.seed(1234)
attach(fm.train)
ctree <- rpart(return~.,data=fm.train,method="class",
  parms=list(split="information"))
summary(ctree)
